lternative, regionally based perspectives on Asia’s contemporary dynamics. This critical analysis urges the Canadian government to chart an independent policy, arguing that whatever Canada might gain from following its traditional allies, it equally stands to lose by aligning itself with a consortium of states committed to self-preservation over regional stability.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311127195808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packagez978311143542808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311140824840uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077486861740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774868617423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774868617/original  a978-3-11-127195-8  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-140824-8  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-143542-8  ACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packageb2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles